table.name: monthly_population_vic
table.Comment: Population growth in Victoria per month. From now data covers 1902/12/01 until 2005/01/01. Need to complete data until 2019.

table.name: actors
table.Comment: Actors table taken from the actor-actor relationship DB.

table.name: cpi_conversion
table.Comment: Data to correct prices using CPI. From 1901 to 1965 in pre-decimal and 1966 onwards in decimal system, corrected at 2018 prices. For future CPI, I used the forecasts from https://www.rba.gov.au/publications/smp/2019/aug/forecasts.html

table.name: domestic_consumers
table.Comment: Number of domestic consumers per year. The total of domestic consumers is given at the last month of each year e.g. 1935-12-01.

table.name: generation_demand_historic
table.Comment: Merge of generation data from open NEM, Demand data VIC and SECV data

table.name: generationassets
table.Comment: This list contains all the generators that have participated in the Electricity system in Victoria since the early days. The list follows the latest format used by the NEM to publish the generation information in all the Australian market. The latest information can be found here:https://www.aemo.com.au/Electricity/National-Electricity-Market-NEM/Planning-and-forecasting/Generation-information This list include "large-scale PV systems" until November 2019, published on this source: https://pv-map.apvi.org.au/power-stations

table.name: household_forecast_victoria
table.Comment: Product developed by DEWLP. Column orders and type of file modified to be included in the model. "Population, households and dwellings for Victoria in Future Small Areas (VIFSA) and Local Government Areas (LGA) from 2016 to 2036. The spatial units used in these projections are based on the Australian Statistical Geography Standard (ASGS) and Local Government Authority boundaries as at 30 June 2016, as well as Victoria in Future Small Areas (VIFSA). VIFSAs are sub-LGA areas defined by DELWP, based on Statistical Area Level 2 of the ASGS. For more information on the definition of VIFSAs, including illustrations and dowloadable GIS files, see the website listed below. http://www.delwp.vic.gov.au/planning/forward-policy-and-research/victoria-in-future-population-and-household-projections/geographic-areas"

table.name: isp_annual_consumption
table.Comment: Forecast from the integrated system plan launched in 2019. This table holds actual annual consumption from 2010 and different forecasts from 2019 to 2050. The data from ISP and ESOO is partially merged. only the "Actual" values are taken from the ESOO 2019 from: http://forecasting.aemo.com.au/Electricity/AnnualConsumption/Operational The effective date of this forecasts is 29/10/2019. Forecasts include scenarios of "central", "fast change", "High DER", "Slow change", and "Step change". Details on demand forecasts are here: https://www.aemo.com.au/-/media/Files/Electricity/NEM/Planning_and_Forecasting/NEM_ESOO/2018/Electricity-Demand-Forecasting-Methodology-Information-Paper.pdf

table.name: isp_maximum_demand
table.Comment: Maximum demand forecast in MW per year from the ISP 2019. More info here: http://forecasting.aemo.com.au/Electricity/MaximumDemand/Operational Effective date 29/10/2019 "For maximum demand, the top 10 highest demand half hours each year were used to calculate the average generation at time of maximum demand. For minimum demand, de bottom 10 demand periods were used." (page. 31, Electricity Demand Forecasting Methodology Information paper February 2019.)

table.name: isp_minimum_demand
table.Comment: Maximum demand forecast in MW per year from the ISP 2019. More info here: http://forecasting.aemo.com.au/Electricity/MaximumDemand/Operational Effective date 29/10/2019 "For maximum demand, the top 10 highest demand half hours each year were used to calculate the average generation at time of maximum demand. For minimum demand, de bottom 10 demand periods were used." (page. 31, Electricity Demand Forecasting Methodology Information paper February 2019.)

table.name: networkassets
table.Comment: Nov 2019. Update of network assets table.

table.name: population_high_forecast_victoria
table.Comment: Forecast from http://stat.data.abs.gov.au/Index.aspx?Queryid=1079 includes forecast data from 2017 to 2066. This model uses data from 2019. -High fertility -High life expectancy -High net overseas migration -large interstate flows Data extracted on 12 Nov 2019 01:51 UTC (GMT) from ABS.Stat © Commonwealth of Australia. Creative Commons Attribution 2.5 Australia (https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/2.5/au)

table.name: population_low_forecast_victoria
table.Comment:
Forecast downloaded from http://stat.data.abs.gov.au/Index.aspx?Queryid=1079 with data from 2017 to 2066. Data from 2019 is used in this model.
Assumptions from this forecast: -Low fertility -Medium life expectancy -Low net overseas migration - small interstate flows
Data extracted on 12 Nov 2019 01:58 UTC (GMT) from ABS.Stat © Commonwealth of Australia. Creative Commons Attribution 2.5 Australia (https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/2.5/au)

table.name: population_medium_forecast_victoria
table.Comment:
Source of the forecast: http://stat.data.abs.gov.au/Index.aspx?Queryid=1079 The forecast has different assumptions in terms of fertility, mortaility, and overseas and interstate migration. The forecast in this table is taken with the assumptions of: - Medium fertility - Medium life expectancy - Medium net overseas migration - Medium interstate flows
Data extracted on 12 Nov 2019 01:43 UTC (GMT) from ABS.Stat © Commonwealth of Australia. Creative Commons Attribution 2.5 Australia (https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/2.5/au)

table.name: solar_exposure_monthly
table.Comment: Monthly mean daily global solar exposure (MJ/m*m) http://www.bom.gov.au/ Data for the Melbourne Olympic Park station

table.name: solar_ghi
table.Comment: Solar historic data downloaded from https://www.nationalmap.gov.au/renewables, which is downloaded from http://www.bom.gov.au/climate/data/oneminsolar/about-IDCJAC0022.shtml Data was processed, therefore this file only contains the 30 minute mean (from minute data) of the Globa Horizontal Irradiation in in w/ sq m. The data is from the station 086282, which corresponds to Melbourne Airport.

table.name: solar_installation_monthly
table.Comment: Number of installations per month from 2007. Original source of data: https://pv-map.apvi.org.au/postcode

table.name: spm
table.Comment: Nov 2019. Keep the numbers of the SPMs since they have generators allocated depending on their capacity. Until this date: 1 Conventional (not used) 2 DER generation (not used) 3 DER generation and battery (not used) 4 off-grid + battery (not used) 5 Distribution 6 Subtransmission 7 Transmission (not used) 8 Industry (not used) 9 Large generation unit (not used) 10 Large generation unit + battery (not used) 11 Off-site small generation unit (not used) 12 Off-site small generation unit + battery (not used)

table.name: tariffdata
table.Comment: Includes the tariffs for the 4 case study areas from 1900 to 1990

table.name: total_demand_halfhour
table.Comment: Total Demand data AEMO. From 1999 to 2019. 30 minute data.

table.name: totaldemandvictoria
table.Comment: Total Demand in Victoria from Dec 1998 to Jul 2019 each 30 minutes. Demand is in MW. Downloaded from https://www.aemo.com.au/Electricity/National-Electricity-Market-NEM/Data-dashboard#aggregated-data

table.name: wind30min_mtmercer
table.Comment: 30 min Wind data from Jan 2015 to July 2018.

column.name: reg_number
column.Comment: Registration ID in Australian databases. Can be the ABN (for companies created or registered after 1999), the ARN or other type of id.

column.name: role
column.Comment: Types are: Generator, Utility-retailer, EnergyInstitution, GovAuthority, Intending, Investor, Market, NetworkOp, OtherAuthority, Services, Household, Industry.

column.name: date

column.Comment: Contains all regions of the NEM

column.name: asset_type
column.Comment: Includes "Lighting System", "Existing plant", "Non-existing Plant", and "Project".

column.name: site_name
column.Comment: Name of the power station pre and during NEM. Some old power stations that have been upgraded and are still functioning (e.g. Rubicon, Loy Yang A) hold one unique id regardless on changes in management or ownership over time. This changes are recorded in the "actor-asset" table (though some details may be found in the owner name column).

column.name: owner_name
column.Comment: This is just for information purposes. Changes in ownership or management are recorded in the "actor-asset" tables.

column.name: technology_type
column.Comment: Details on technology (e.g. Turbine - Steam Sub Critical)

column.name: fuel_type
column.Comment: Specific fuel type (e.g. Brown coal, biogas, biomas, etc)

column.name: duid
column.Comment: Unit id, if available, by which a unit is recognised in the NEM (e.g. MORTLK11 for Mortlake or JLA03 for unit 3 of Jeerlang A)

column.name: no_units

column.name: nameplate_capacity_mw
column.Comment: Capacity in MW of the asset. Some projects provide a range as this number might not be already determined, for these cases, the median capacity is assumed.

column.name: storage_capacity_mwh

column.name: unit_status
column.Comment: Status of the unit includes "Commited", "Emerging", "Decomissioned", "Maturing", "In-Service", etc .

column.name: dispatch_type

column.Comment: The name of the tariff. Might correspond to an organisation name, but it is not always the case.

column.name: firstxunits_dkwh
column.Comment: This tariff corresponds to the description of rates from 1900 to 1905. It is given in pre-decimal system. The x corresponds to 20 units in this case and the demand was mostly public lighting, commercial and few industries.

column.name: afterxunits_dkwh
column.Comment: This tariff corresponds to the description of rates from 1900 to 1905. It is given in pre-decimal system. The x corresponds to 20 units in this case and the demand was mostly public lighting, commercial and few industries.

column.name: lightsecondxunits_dkwh
column.Comment: Light charges second x units in pre-decimal system. X in 1906 corresponded to 1000 units.

column.name: lightthirdxunits_dkwh

column.name: lightthereafter_dkwh

column.name: threeroomsgbgdgrfirstx_ckwhquarter
column.Comment: Residential 3 rooms or less "GB"/"GD"/"GR" First X units per quarter starts in 1971. X varies with time. The charge is in decimal system. The G, GB, GD and GR tariffs are included in this column depending on the year.

column.name: threeroomsgbgdgrnextx_ckwhquarter
column.Comment: Residential 3 rooms or less "GB"/"GD"/"GR" Next X units per quarter starts in 1971. X varies with time. The charge is in decimal system. The G, GB, GD and GR tariffs are included in this column depending on the year.

column.name: threeroomsgbgdgrbalance_ckwhquarter
column.Comment: Residential 3 rooms or less "GB"/"GD"/"GR" balance X units per quarter starts in 1971. X varies with time. The charge is in decimal system. The G, GB, GD and GR tariffs are included in this column depending on the year.

column.name: jfirstx_ckwhquarter
column.Comment: J tariff in decimal system. The x represents 1200kwh per quarter in 1969.

column.name: jbalance_ckwhquarter
column.Comment: J tariff in decimal system. The balance of the J tariff from SECV.

column.name: secvij_gdgr_aud_quarter
column.Comment: SECV tariffs I&J (space and water heating) and residential GD and GR. Charges are in dollars per quarter.

column.name: jy_aud_quarter

column.name: energycharge_cdkwh
column.Comment: Tariff energy in d/unit or c/kWh. Sometimes coincide with the average price per tariff. It might be given in pre-decimal or decimal system. Fix rates are not included.

column.name: standingcharge_aud_year
